When a global exception translator is registered, it will be applied across all modules in the reverse order of registration. This can create behavior where the order of module import influences how exceptions are translated. If module1 has the following translator: py::register_exception_translator([](std::exception_ptr p) { try { if (p) std::rethrow_exception(p); } catch (const std::invalid_argument &e) { PyErr_SetString("module1 handled this") }
} and module2 has the following similar translator: py::register_exception_translator([](std::exception_ptr p) { try { if (p) std::rethrow_exception(p); } catch (const std::invalid_argument &e) { PyErr_SetString("module2 handled this") }
} then which translator handles the invalid_argument will be determined by the order that module1 and module2 are imported. Since exception translators are applied in the reverse order of registration, which ever module was imported last will “win” and that translator will be applied. If there are multiple pybind11 modules that share exception types (either standard built-in or custom) loaded into a single python instance and consistent error handling behavior is needed, then local translators should be used. Changing the previous example to use register_local_exception_translator would mean that when invalid_argument is thrown in the module2 code, the module2 translator will always handle it, while in module1, the module1 translator will do the same.

